##Usage


AGE - Overrides and Customizations
* Use custom source for main configuration file 

        class { '<%= metadata.name %>':
          config_file_source => [ "puppet:///modules/example42/<%= metadata.name %>/<%= metadata.name %>.conf-${hostname}" ,
                           "puppet:///modules/example42/<%= metadata.name %>/<%= metadata.name %>.conf" ], 
        }


* Use custom source directory for the whole configuration dir.

        class { '<%= metadata.name %>':
          config_dir_source  => 'puppet:///modules/example42/<%= metadata.name %>/conf/',
        }

* Use custom source directory for the whole configuration dir purging all the local files that are not on the dir.
  Note: This option can be used to be sure that the content of a directory is exactly the same you expect, but it is desctructive and may remove files.

        class { '<%= metadata.name %>':
          config_dir_source => 'puppet:///modules/example42/<%= metadata.name %>/conf/',
          config_dir_purge  => true, # Default: false.
        }

* Use custom source directory for the whole configuration dir and define recursing policy.

        class { '<%= metadata.name %>':
          config_dir_source    => 'puppet:///modules/example42/<%= metadata.name %>/conf/',
          config_dir_recursion => false, # Default: true.
        }

* Use custom template for main config file. Note that template and source arguments are alternative.

        class { '<%= metadata.name %>':
          config_file_template => 'example42/<%= metadata.name %>/<%= metadata.name %>.conf.erb',
        }

* Use a custom template and provide an hash of custom configurations that you can use inside the template

        class { '<%= metadata.name %>':
          config_file_template      => 'example42/<%= metadata.name %>/<%= metadata.name %>.conf.erb',
          config_file_options_hash  => {
            opt  => 'value',
            opt2 => 'value2',
          },
        }



* Automatically include a custom class with extra resources related to <%= metadata.name %>.
  Here is loaded $modulepath/example42/manifests/my_<%= metadata.name %>.pp.
  Note: Use a subclass name different than <%= metadata.name %> to avoid order loading issues.

        class { '<%= metadata.name %>':
         my_class => 'site::<%= metadata.name %>_my',
        }


